BOTULISM, AVIAN - CANADA: (ALBERTA)
***********************************

A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Sat 13 Aug 2011
Source: French Tribune [edited]
http://www.frenchtribune.com/teneur/116660-avian-botulism-may-lead-extreme-bird-deaths-around-alberta-warn-experts


An outbreak of avian botulism will result in extreme bird deaths
around Alberta lakes, warned the experts. The disease is already
blamed for bird deaths on Utikuma Lake north of Lesser Slave Lake, and
Pakowki Lake as well, south of Medicine Hat. However, the carcasses
have not appeared to cause any deaths among humans.

The warmer weather of [this] month [August 2011] has contributed
enough to provide feasible environment for the outbreak along with
formation of blue-green algae blooms on lakes. In addition, the algae
decomposition is likely to produce a toxin capable of affecting fish
and birds and in some cases may also distress humans. Consequently,
the government has placed warnings in areas where water quality
becomes unsafe.

"With heavy rain falls and shallow lakes, there is a bacterium that
creates the botulism toxin and it can get into insects," notified
Darcy Whiteside, Spokesman for Alberta Sustainable Resource
Development. "The birds eat the maggots and then it builds up and
basically kills the birds. The numbers of deaths can get pretty high,
into the thousands in some of the larger lakes."

The outbreaks are triggered naturally having an influence from
increased rainfalls and warmer temperature. Authorities in Alberta
have outlined policies to monitor blue-green algae blooms.

[Byline: Nimisha Sachdev]

