Communicated by:
HealthMap Alerts via ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[When there is enough of proper nutrients in the water and conditions
are correct there can be a bloom of toxic algae, generally blue-green
algae. Blue-green algae can be very toxic and can cause sudden death
in animals consuming the water.

When an animal dies and the bacterium _Clostridium botulinum_ grows
and produces the botulinum toxin, then flies lay eggs. The maggots
bioaccumulate the botulism toxin. Other birds eat the maggots and
become affected by botulism. Consequently, unless dead carcasses are
picked up, then the cycle continues.

Let us hope the dead birds and fish or other animals around these
water sources are quickly cleaned up. - Mod.TG]

[Maps of Alberta can be seen at
http://www.canada-maps.org/alberta/images/alberta-map.gif and
http://healthmap.org/r/1950. - Sr.Tech.Ed.MJ]
